1Ô∏è‚É£ Route 53

Amazon Route 53 is a scalable DNS (Domain Name System) web service.
It routes user requests to AWS resources like EC2, ELB, or S3.

2Ô∏è‚É£ Domain Registration

Route 53 allows you to register and manage domain names.
AWS becomes the DNS provider for the domain.

3Ô∏è‚É£ Hosted Zones

A hosted zone contains DNS records for a domain.
It defines how domain names are translated to IP addresses.

4Ô∏è‚É£ DNS Records

Route 53 supports records like A, AAAA, CNAME, MX, and TXT.
These records map domain names to resources.

5Ô∏è‚É£ Routing Policies

Route 53 provides multiple routing policies such as Simple, Weighted, Latency-based, Failover, and Geolocation.
They control how traffic is routed to resources.

6Ô∏è‚É£ Health Checks

Route 53 health checks monitor the health of endpoints.
Traffic is routed only to healthy resources.

7Ô∏è‚É£ Failover Routing

Failover routing automatically redirects traffic to a backup resource.
It improves application availability during failures.

8Ô∏è‚É£ Alias Records

Alias records map domains to AWS resources like ELB or CloudFront.
They are AWS-specific and do not charge for DNS queries.

9Ô∏è‚É£ Security

Route 53 integrates with IAM for access control.
It supports DNSSEC for domain security.

üîü Use Cases

Route 53 is used for domain management, traffic routing, and high availability.
It ensures fast and reliable DNS resolution.
